    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>War and Diplomacy: A Week of Decision on Iraq</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Eric Chivian, co-founder, International Physicians for Prevention of Nuclear War, says Bush administration's diplomacy is hardly the way to inspire trust or cooperation</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Quarrel Over Iraq Gets Ugly'' (Week in Review, Jan. 26):</p>
        <p>Demonizing other countries, leaving no room for them to be anything other than our enemies; embarrassing and insulting our allies; thumbing our nose at the United Nations and one international treaty after another; and bullying and threatening everyone to do things our way or no way:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Quarrel Over Iraq Gets Ugly'' (Week in Review, Jan. 26):</p>
        <p>Demonizing other countries, leaving no room for them to be anything other than our enemies; embarrassing and insulting our allies; thumbing our nose at the United Nations and one international treaty after another; and bullying and threatening everyone to do things our way or no way:</p>
        <p>While this may be the Bush administration's idea of diplomacy, it is hardly the way to inspire the trust or cooperation necessary for the war on terrorism, environmental degradation or the other global crises we face.</p>
        <p>ERIC CHIVIAN, M.D.  Boston, Jan. 26, 2003</p>
        <p>The writer is a co-founder, International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War, which won the 1985 Nobel Peace Prize.</p>
      </block>
